you're going to be able to hire a lot more diverse team.

80
00:03:05,689 --> 00:03:08,191
Overwhelmingly, the people with free time and capital

81
00:03:08,491 --> 00:03:10,493
are English-speaking North American white men,

82
00:03:11,634 --> 00:03:14,156
people that look like me and the other business partner who

83
00:03:14,216 --> 00:03:15,136
is involved in this equation.

84
00:03:16,277 --> 00:03:18,119
Many people can't work speculatively.

85
00:03:18,219 --> 00:03:20,801
Some people need a stable job, no matter how talented

86
00:03:20,841 --> 00:03:21,441
or driven they are.

87
00:03:21,741 --> 00:03:23,323
If you can offer people real employment

88
00:03:23,363 --> 00:03:24,403
while you're running your studio,

89
00:03:24,824 --> 00:03:27,186
you're going to have access to a much larger pool of talent,

90
00:03:27,226 --> 00:03:28,547
and it's going to make everything a lot easier.

91
00:03:30,962 --> 00:03:33,403
So now, before you actually start your studio,

92
00:03:33,423 --> 00:03:34,363
before you do anything at all,

93
00:03:34,383 --> 00:03:36,084
there's just a few quick tips I'd like to give you.

94
00:03:37,364 --> 00:03:38,885
First, these two things are really important

95
00:03:38,905 --> 00:03:39,405
if you can do it.

96
00:03:39,625 --> 00:03:43,266
One, have an entire year's worth of runway before you begin.

97
00:03:43,366 --> 00:03:45,707
Even if you don't make a single dollar in the first year,

98
00:03:45,747 --> 00:03:46,648
you should be okay.

99
00:03:47,028 --> 00:03:47,848
Try and plan around this.

100
00:03:47,888 --> 00:03:50,029
You might not need it for all 365 days,

101
00:03:50,049 --> 00:03:51,789
but you'll be really grateful that you had it.

102
00:03:52,450 --> 00:03:55,192
Two, if you are currently employed, get credit now.

103
00:03:55,312 --> 00:03:57,574
This seems super evident to be in retrospect,

104
00:03:57,895 --> 00:04:00,677
but it is way easier to get credit if you have a stable job

105
00:04:00,897 --> 00:04:04,020
than if you are an unemployed person who owns a studio with no value.

106
00:04:04,541 --> 00:04:07,023
Right? Try and do both of these first.

107
00:04:08,064 --> 00:04:10,907
But third, and this is my most important takeaway from the entire talk.

108
00:04:11,644 --> 00:04:12,785
is get a mentor, right?

109
00:04:12,925 --> 00:04:14,626
My previous statements about, like,

110
00:04:14,706 --> 00:04:15,707
I don't have the answers,

111
00:04:15,787 --> 00:04:18,588
is because my advice to you is not contextual, right?

112
00:04:18,628 --> 00:04:20,129
Like, you're gonna find someone

113
00:04:20,189 --> 00:04:21,450
who's in the space you're in,

114
00:04:21,710 --> 00:04:23,711
who's in the physical location is who's in,

115
00:04:23,892 --> 00:04:25,573
who's doing the kind of stuff you wanna be doing,

116
00:04:25,853 --> 00:04:26,653
who's bigger than you are.

117
00:04:26,853 --> 00:04:28,574
Someone who's already gone through the growing pains

118
00:04:28,594 --> 00:04:30,135
that you are hopefully going to go through.

119
00:04:30,456 --> 00:04:32,457
That person will be able to give you much better advice

120
00:04:32,477 --> 00:04:34,058
than anything in this talk I can give you.

121
00:04:34,338 --> 00:04:36,699
If you remember only one thing from my talk,

122
00:04:37,040 --> 00:04:38,040
let it be this one point.

123
00:04:40,278 --> 00:04:41,818
So now we're getting into the part of the talk

124
00:04:41,838 --> 00:04:43,219
that arguably everyone cares about.

125
00:04:43,979 --> 00:04:45,700
And that's how do you actually get client work?

126
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:47,000
And I'm gonna begin with a spoiler.

127
00:04:47,020 --> 00:04:50,461
All right, this is an age test.

128
00:04:50,481 --> 00:04:54,403
Okay, it's not this spoiler either.

129
00:04:54,423 --> 00:04:56,123
So what's the spoiler?

130
00:04:56,723 --> 00:04:56,983
This one.

131
00:04:57,906 --> 00:04:59,047
There's no magic wand.

132
00:04:59,107 --> 00:05:00,628
There's no secret trick.

133
00:05:00,668 --> 00:05:02,569
There's no directory of client work

134
00:05:02,609 --> 00:05:03,810
that you can go onto online

135
00:05:04,130 --> 00:05:06,391
that only me and a handful of people know about.

136
00:05:06,411 --> 00:05:08,633
There's no list of potential clients.

137
00:05:08,893 --> 00:05:11,234
There's no one trick that game devs hate.

138
00:05:11,495 --> 00:05:12,575
There's nothing like that.

139
00:05:12,615 --> 00:05:14,216
It's hard to get client work,

140
00:05:14,436 --> 00:05:15,857
and it's hard to do client work.

141
00:05:17,138 --> 00:05:17,939
Now, with that in mind,

142
00:05:17,979 --> 00:05:19,340
how do you actually do it, even if it's hard?

143
00:05:20,578 --> 00:05:22,379
So the first thing, and people hate this one,

144
00:05:22,660 --> 00:05:23,980
is always be networking.

145
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:25,801
I hear a lot of people grumble about this,

146
00:05:25,901 --> 00:05:27,682
and if you manage to succeed without doing this,

147
00:05:27,702 --> 00:05:28,543
you are a unicorn,

148
00:05:28,563 --> 00:05:30,564
and you probably don't need any of my advice.

149
00:05:31,204 --> 00:05:32,225
You're gonna need clients,

150
00:05:32,625 --> 00:05:33,686
you're gonna need employees,

151
00:05:33,706 --> 00:05:34,646
you're gonna need friends,

152
00:05:34,666 --> 00:05:35,607
you're gonna need allies,

153
00:05:35,627 --> 00:05:36,527
you're gonna need publishers,

154
00:05:36,547 --> 00:05:37,788
you're gonna need everything under the sun,

155
00:05:37,988 --> 00:05:39,228
and you don't know what you're gonna need

156
00:05:39,269 --> 00:05:40,649
before you need it.

157
00:05:40,989 --> 00:05:42,850
These people are going to be your future clients,

158
00:05:42,890 --> 00:05:44,031
they're gonna be your future partners,

159
00:05:44,051 --> 00:05:45,132
they're gonna help you ship games,

160
00:05:45,152 --> 00:05:46,352
they're gonna help you do work,

161
00:05:46,372 --> 00:05:47,113
they're gonna give you money.

162
00:05:48,277 --> 00:05:50,337
Networking puts you in contact with other people,

163
00:05:50,397 --> 00:05:51,198
and people matter.

164
00:05:53,279 --> 00:05:53,939
Grow your team.

165
00:05:55,099 --> 00:05:56,760
Provide solutions, not labor.

166
00:05:56,820 --> 00:05:59,081
What I mean by this is become a full service outfit.

167
00:05:59,401 --> 00:06:01,542
Try and avoid single contributor contracts.

168
00:06:01,822 --> 00:06:03,643
What you wanna be doing is you wanna be pitching things

169
00:06:03,683 --> 00:06:06,684
like features, or ports, or full games.

170
00:06:07,004 --> 00:06:07,945
You wanna be offering something

171
00:06:07,965 --> 00:06:09,805
that there isn't an obvious substitution for.

172
00:06:12,759 --> 00:06:14,740
Now, how do you get those ones?

173
00:06:14,800 --> 00:06:15,861
Is you want to be climbing the ladder.

174
00:06:15,901 --> 00:06:17,542
I know I just said go broad at the beginning

175
00:06:17,562 --> 00:06:19,063
and network like literally all the time.

176
00:06:19,363 --> 00:06:21,025
What we also want to be doing is your clients

177
00:06:21,065 --> 00:06:22,886
are overwhelmingly going to be organizations

178
00:06:23,266 --> 00:06:24,507
that are a little bit bigger than you.

179
00:06:24,927 --> 00:06:27,049
Really big orgs, sometimes you'll get work for them,

180
00:06:27,089 --> 00:06:28,469
but there's a ton of other people in the mix

181
00:06:28,490 --> 00:06:29,170
to get those jobs.

182
00:06:29,530 --> 00:06:31,532
And organizations and studios that are the exact

183
00:06:31,552 --> 00:06:33,673
same size as you, you probably can't hire them.

184
00:06:33,913 --> 00:06:35,774
So remember, they probably can't hire you.

185
00:06:36,175 --> 00:06:37,475
There will be exceptions to this,

186
00:06:37,535 --> 00:06:40,057
but generally speaking, always be trying to target

187
00:06:40,077 --> 00:06:41,798
the people who are just a bit bigger than you.

188
00:06:42,359 --> 00:06:44,319
And if you continue to grow year over year,

189
00:06:44,499 --> 00:06:46,139
you're gonna be meeting new members

190
00:06:46,299 --> 00:06:47,640
of those ladders of rungs.

191
00:06:47,660 --> 00:06:49,020
So you're gonna wanna meet a whole bunch of people

192
00:06:49,080 --> 00:06:51,701
one year and the next year, the group after that.

193
00:06:52,961 --> 00:06:55,682
Also, don't always look for game studios.

194
00:06:55,962 --> 00:06:58,602
Look for games adjacent clients, non-games clients.

195
00:06:58,922 --> 00:07:00,963
The advantages of these are manifold.

196
00:07:01,443 --> 00:07:02,663
Being a direct contractor means

197
00:07:02,683 --> 00:07:04,023
you can command better rates,

198
00:07:04,083 --> 00:07:06,504
there's not an obvious substitution to internal development,

199
00:07:06,904 --> 00:07:08,625
and just everything's easier.

200
00:07:08,665 --> 00:07:10,285
If you can get these kind of contracts to do,

201
00:07:10,305 --> 00:07:11,905
you'll make your life a lot more straightforward.

202
00:07:13,974 --> 00:07:16,975
This one also seems pretty obvious to me, but I haven't fought hard enough for it,

203
00:07:17,456 --> 00:07:22,118
and it's really hurt us in the long run, is get attribution. You want to start from a point

204
00:07:22,458 --> 00:07:26,020
where your game studio's name is at the very beginning of the game you're working along

205
00:07:26,040 --> 00:07:29,521
with all of the other studios on it. You're not going to get that, but that's going to be the

206
00:07:29,561 --> 00:07:33,563
point you want to start in negotiations and work your way back from them. Attribution lets other

207
00:07:33,603 --> 00:07:36,824
people know what you've done, and that's really important for getting future work,

208
00:07:37,064 --> 00:07:38,765
and we've been bad about that, and it's hurt us.

209
00:07:40,604 --> 00:07:42,005
However, we've been really good about this one,

210
00:07:42,085 --> 00:07:43,345
and I know this seems pretty obvious,

211
00:07:43,405 --> 00:07:44,946
but you get so much out of this.

212
00:07:46,047 --> 00:07:47,948
Deliver on time and deliver on budget.

213
00:07:48,068 --> 00:07:50,849
Be involved in the project estimation and get good at it.

214
00:07:51,169 --> 00:07:53,350
People are gonna tell other people that you're good at this

215
00:07:53,650 --> 00:07:56,172
and this is completely invaluable in this industry.

216
00:07:56,572 --> 00:07:57,852
Very few people are good at this

217
00:07:58,113 --> 00:07:59,333
and it's gonna get you a lot of work.

218
00:08:00,053 --> 00:08:01,554
Also, working on your own games,

219
00:08:01,894 --> 00:08:03,235
it's really good at being good at this.

220
00:08:03,415 --> 00:08:05,596
Like, knowing that you're gonna launch your own title

221
00:08:05,636 --> 00:08:07,697
on a particular timeline is really gonna help you.

222
00:08:09,987 --> 00:08:12,067
So how do you balance this against internal development?

223
00:08:13,548 --> 00:08:16,349
Now, keep in mind that all of the other stuff I just said

224
00:08:16,389 --> 00:08:18,109
is going to seriously burn you out creatively.

225
00:08:18,489 --> 00:08:20,070
I personally struggle with this a lot.

226
00:08:20,630 --> 00:08:22,751
Development on our games suffers from my focus on business

227
00:08:22,791 --> 00:08:25,612
issues, and I'm not entirely clear on how I'm supposed

228
00:08:25,632 --> 00:08:26,612
to compartmentalize those.

229
00:08:27,152 --> 00:08:29,733
Just be aware that getting and delivering client work

230
00:08:29,773 --> 00:08:30,854
is going to take a lot out of you

231
00:08:30,894 --> 00:08:32,314
and is going to take a lot out of your focus

232
00:08:32,354 --> 00:08:34,295
on a creative endeavor, like launching your first game.

233
00:08:34,775 --> 00:08:35,235
Let me know how.

234
00:08:35,335 --> 00:08:36,636
If you figure out how to solve this,

235
00:08:36,736 --> 00:08:37,816
I still haven't figured this one out.

236
00:08:39,714 --> 00:08:42,036
This lack of focus has really tangible impacts

237
00:08:42,076 --> 00:08:43,096
on your internal development.

238
00:08:43,537 --> 00:08:46,719
Don't assume that just because you have 50% of the time

239
00:08:46,739 --> 00:08:48,780
that you're gonna make a game in half the time.

240
00:08:49,060 --> 00:08:50,601
It's probably more like three times.

241
00:08:51,642 --> 00:08:54,063
Working on something a lot gives you a lot of deep focus

242
00:08:54,163 --> 00:08:55,884
and allows you to involve in deep collaboration

243
00:08:55,904 --> 00:08:57,285
which really improves your productivity.

244
00:08:57,606 --> 00:09:00,007
If you're like switching between different games

245
00:09:00,047 --> 00:09:01,648
like clients games and your games,

246
00:09:01,928 --> 00:09:03,109
you're not gonna be as effective.

247
00:09:03,409 --> 00:09:05,070
If you have a timeline that says it's gonna come out

248
00:09:05,090 --> 00:09:06,851
in a year, it's actually gonna be three.

