00:09:27,415 --> 00:09:28,776
that have nothing to do with your game.

259
00:09:29,076 --> 00:09:30,717
Maybe they have a graphic design acubent.

260
00:09:30,997 --> 00:09:32,898
Maybe they have 2D animation skills,

261
00:09:32,918 --> 00:09:33,999
but you're making a 3D game.

262
00:09:34,219 --> 00:09:35,939
You're going to people who can wear a ton of hats

263
00:09:35,979 --> 00:09:36,500
to make this work.

264
00:09:38,702 --> 00:09:41,864
And last but not least, protect your team from sales thrash.

265
00:09:42,065 --> 00:09:43,426
It's gonna be really tough, you're gonna be out there

266
00:09:43,466 --> 00:09:44,927
trying to get new contracts.

267
00:09:45,408 --> 00:09:47,129
Don't expose your team to all of this.

268
00:09:47,550 --> 00:09:48,751
You're already stressed out about it,

269
00:09:49,011 --> 00:09:51,573
you don't need your 3D modeler panicking

270
00:09:51,593 --> 00:09:52,914
about whether or not you got that contract.

271
00:09:53,235 --> 00:09:55,136
Be somewhat transparent so they understand

272
00:09:55,176 --> 00:09:57,979
the health of the studio, but every single potential client

273
00:09:58,059 --> 00:09:59,840
doesn't need to be your employee's problems.

274
00:10:00,561 --> 00:10:03,744
Anyway, I'm running out of time, and I hope this was brief but helpful.

275
00:10:04,185 --> 00:10:07,047
And it was really tough for us to do this, and I'm sure it's going to be tough for you.

276
00:10:07,388 --> 00:10:10,891
So if you want any help, reach out to me on Twitter or talk to me after the talk.

277
00:10:11,111 --> 00:10:13,574
I'd love to get a little bit more in the weeds on this, I just don't have the time.

278
00:10:14,034 --> 00:10:14,515
Thank you so much.

279
00:10:14,535 --> 00:10:23,243
All right.

280
00:10:24,493 --> 00:10:31,928
I'm Teresa Derringer and I'm going to speak a little bit more towards the specifics of how to run a studio without a surprise hit

281
00:10:32,389 --> 00:10:34,413
using hardware and IP partnerships.

282
00:10:37,234 --> 00:10:40,377
So we've all heard about indie mega hit darlings,

283
00:10:40,937 --> 00:10:44,620
the hotline Miamis, Fezzes, Bastions, and Braids,

284
00:10:45,180 --> 00:10:47,722
but I would venture that at least some of the people

285
00:10:47,782 --> 00:10:50,425
in this room are not working on the top five

286
00:10:50,465 --> 00:10:51,405
grossing indie games.

287
00:10:52,246 --> 00:10:54,868
However unflattering it is to address this subject,

288
00:10:54,988 --> 00:10:56,449
it's worth being honest about.

289
00:10:57,030 --> 00:11:01,273
The truth is that most indie games are not household names,

290
00:11:02,394 --> 00:11:02,894
mine included.

291
00:11:04,544 --> 00:11:10,670
So while it's really obvious what to do if you have a total hit, which is keep at it, awesome,

292
00:11:11,310 --> 00:11:14,774
or if you have a total flop, you know, maybe do something else,

293
00:11:15,414 --> 00:11:20,619
there's a question of what do you do if your game is somewhere in between?

294
00:11:21,480 --> 00:11:24,943
And it's a really tough question, it's kind of embarrassing to ask,

295
00:11:25,804 --> 00:11:28,366
and it's a question I've had to ask myself.

296
00:11:29,446 --> 00:11:31,267
With my first indie game, Cannon Brawl,

297
00:11:31,767 --> 00:11:34,928
it made about $400,000 in sales and about $130,000

298
00:11:35,348 --> 00:11:37,269
in contest winnings.

299
00:11:38,009 --> 00:11:41,250
It took two people three years to make, minus Steam's cut.

300
00:11:41,731 --> 00:11:44,692
It was about $70,000 per person per year.

301
00:11:46,152 --> 00:11:49,073
It's not nothing, but it's certainly not

302
00:11:49,113 --> 00:11:49,974
time to buy a yacht.

303
00:11:50,794 --> 00:11:54,295
So where do you go from here if your game is kind of like

304
00:11:54,515 --> 00:11:55,656
somewhere in between?

305
00:11:56,881 --> 00:12:02,645
After a big launch, it can be really tough to get going on the next thing or even know what that next thing is.

306
00:12:03,126 --> 00:12:06,428
But that's the most important thing for you to be doing right at that moment.

307
00:12:07,028 --> 00:12:08,609
So you just have to pick a direction.

308
00:12:08,629 --> 00:12:12,812
And for me, with Cannon Brawl, we got started because it had won a contest.

309
00:12:13,913 --> 00:12:17,375
So we found another contest and that was the Oculus VR Jam.

310
00:12:17,955 --> 00:12:21,057
And don't worry, this talk is not going to be about contests.

311
00:12:22,078 --> 00:12:24,519
But it can be helpful to identify one thing,

312
00:12:25,179 --> 00:12:29,922
which is who has too much money and not enough video games?

313
00:12:33,224 --> 00:12:34,065
Well, not VC.

314
00:12:36,661 --> 00:12:39,524
For a lot of economic reasons, I can't get into a 10-minute talk.

315
00:12:39,884 --> 00:12:43,508
Funding is not usually available to small, creative studios like ours.

316
00:12:45,170 --> 00:12:45,550
Usually.

317
00:12:46,091 --> 00:12:50,035
But there is an exception, and that is with speculative hardware.

318
00:12:50,575 --> 00:12:54,399
So we saw with VR, there was a burst of new funding in the scene,

319
00:12:54,479 --> 00:12:58,463
but we've seen it before with other kinds of hardware, like the PS Vita and OUYA.

320
00:12:59,284 --> 00:13:03,326
And our team's been pretty bullish about this speculative hardware we've developed for Gear,

321
00:13:03,566 --> 00:13:10,690
Vive, Rift, Tango, Starbreeze, even Ciftio. And while it can be really fulfilling to develop for

322
00:13:10,730 --> 00:13:15,752
this exciting new medium, and you're jumping into a community that's really lovely, you're all

323
00:13:15,792 --> 00:13:20,574
fingering it out together, and it feels like you're laying the tracks for the future, I would say

324
00:13:21,034 --> 00:13:26,537
there are some practical reasons to run away. The SDKs are changing out from under you.

325
00:13:27,177 --> 00:13:28,118
There are no standards.

326
00:13:28,904 --> 00:13:31,705
But more importantly, there are no users.

327
00:13:32,746 --> 00:13:36,367
So to give you a sense of my first game in VR,

328
00:13:36,427 --> 00:13:37,328
this was called Bazaar.

329
00:13:38,028 --> 00:13:42,830
And it made $6,000 total on Steam, at least.

330
00:13:43,631 --> 00:13:44,751
That's gross revenue.

331
00:13:45,451 --> 00:13:47,512
Gross being the operative word there.

332
00:13:48,713 --> 00:13:51,374
So without money, at this point, I

333
00:13:51,394 --> 00:13:55,316
would say never develop for speculative hardware,

334
00:13:56,556 --> 00:13:57,957
except if there's money.

335
00:13:58,698 --> 00:14:03,159
So if you have a new platform coming on the market,

336
00:14:03,199 --> 00:14:06,819
especially one in an arms race between hardware manufacturers

337
00:14:07,280 --> 00:14:11,220
or platform interests where they're pouring money into it

338
00:14:11,720 --> 00:14:14,641
and they need content to show off the product,

339
00:14:14,841 --> 00:14:18,142
there is going to be some VC funding for games content.

340
00:14:18,222 --> 00:14:19,482
That's going to make it look good.

341
00:14:20,122 --> 00:14:22,463
You're also going to see grants that are coming directly

342
00:14:22,503 --> 00:14:24,543
from the platform stakeholders themselves,

343
00:14:24,583 --> 00:14:26,143
like we've seen with the Oculus VR.

344
00:14:26,624 --> 00:14:29,066
research grant for $250,000 recently.

345
00:14:30,288 --> 00:14:33,391
In addition to that, you're gonna see other companies

346
00:14:33,692 --> 00:14:35,594
that wanna expand their brands

347
00:14:35,734 --> 00:14:38,076
into this new platform space, the new hotness.

348
00:14:38,116 --> 00:14:41,941
So we saw airlines, TV shows approaching our company

349
00:14:42,281 --> 00:14:44,403
to see if we could help them with that.

350
00:14:45,164 --> 00:14:51,210
So if you've taken the risk of becoming an expert on a piece of hardware where there are relatively

351
00:14:51,270 --> 00:14:58,077
few users, so relatively few developers, you're putting your name in a kind of small hat for

352
00:14:58,117 --> 00:15:04,242
winning contracting bids. Bazaar had absolutely abysmal sales, but it put us on the map as a

353
00:15:04,343 --> 00:15:06,705
studio capable of VR development.

354
00:15:07,345 --> 00:15:12,569
And that's how we were able to get the funding to make Race for the Galaxy in VR from Oculus,

355
00:15:12,830 --> 00:15:19,334
or to do the TAMP with Discovery Channel and do the app for their content on Rift and Gear.

356
00:15:20,762 --> 00:15:23,144
Now you can't always know if that cat is going to,

357
00:15:23,244 --> 00:15:25,486
the hat, not the cat, is going to exist.

358
00:15:26,226 --> 00:15:27,527
You can take some educated guesses

359
00:15:27,587 --> 00:15:30,250
and look and see who's pouring money into the platforms.

360
00:15:30,690 --> 00:15:33,452
But I'd say the biggest way to mitigate your risk here

361
00:15:33,532 --> 00:15:35,994
is to keep your projects to six months and less.

362
00:15:36,554 --> 00:15:39,196
That way if the hat never shows up, you didn't risk it all.

363
00:15:40,537 --> 00:15:42,479
So never develop for a speculative platform,

364
00:15:42,879 --> 00:15:45,882
except if there's money, and also, except if there's IP.

365
00:15:46,917 --> 00:15:51,503
So there's a common catch 22 if you're a studio interested in getting involved with IP work

366
00:15:52,043 --> 00:15:58,271
is that nobody wants to risk their evergreen IP on an unknown developer. So it can be really

367
00:15:58,331 --> 00:16:03,056
hard to get that first one going. But if you can approach an IP holder

368
00:16:03,477 --> 00:16:06,360
With a platform that they're not getting their door knocked down on,

369
00:16:06,601 --> 00:16:07,962
there's not as many competitors,

370
00:16:08,423 --> 00:16:11,266
you can get your foot in the door and build a relationship with them.

371
00:16:11,807 --> 00:16:15,271
And that's how we've gotten some really top-tier board game IPs at our company.

372
00:16:15,711 --> 00:16:16,993
This is how we got Ascension.

373
00:16:17,053 --> 00:16:18,154
They've already got a phone app,

374
00:16:18,394 --> 00:16:22,099
but we were able to approach them with a VR app and get that going.

375
00:16:23,307 --> 00:16:26,130
And once you have one IP, you can really

376
00:16:26,270 --> 00:16:29,853
use this to swing from one to the next and the next,

377
00:16:30,353 --> 00:16:32,355
especially for us with board games,

378
00:16:33,195 --> 00:16:36,138
because many designers have designed more than one game.

379
00:16:36,678 --> 00:16:38,500
Publishers have published more than one game.

380
00:16:38,960 --> 00:16:40,161
So it really helps your flow.

381
00:16:40,802 --> 00:16:42,343
So we started with Ascension VR.

382
00:16:42,563 --> 00:16:45,225
Then we made Race for the Galaxy, Roll for the Galaxy.

383
00:16:45,546 --> 00:16:47,367
And now we're on Shards of Infinity,

384
00:16:47,587 --> 00:16:49,789
which is in beta this week, if anyone wants to give feedback

385
00:16:49,849 --> 00:16:50,089
on that.

386
00:16:51,442 --> 00:16:53,743
And these are all board games on the phone.

387
00:16:54,064 --> 00:16:56,005
They all share the same set of features.

388
00:16:56,045 --> 00:16:57,445
They're all in the same genre.

389
00:16:57,485 --> 00:17:00,827
So board games have a really interesting property,

390
00:17:01,207 --> 00:17:03,148
which is that they come with expansion packs.

391
00:17:03,808 --> 00:17:06,309
And these are these delightful little chunks of work

392
00:17:06,789 --> 00:17:08,770
that are super flexible on your schedule,

393
00:17:08,790 --> 00:17:11,171
and they have a really predictable return.

394
00:17:11,291 --> 00:17:14,073
We find 15% of our sales, our base game sales,

395
00:17:14,413 --> 00:17:16,814
will reap back with our expansions.

396
00:17:18,225 --> 00:17:22,254
Your superpower as an indie studio is you are a unit,

397
00:17:22,274 --> 00:17:25,682
a team of people who work really well together,

398
00:17:26,083 --> 00:17:28,027
especially on small projects.

399
00:17:29,008 --> 00:17:35,433
So you can get a project done faster than a PM at a AAA company can even get the sign-off

400
00:17:35,693 --> 00:17:37,855
on the headcount to do similar work.

401
00:17:38,215 --> 00:17:39,196
So leverage that.

402
00:17:39,956 --> 00:17:43,439
Move around your projects on your schedule so that if someone comes to you and they have

403
00:17:43,479 --> 00:17:47,182
something that needs to get done yesterday, you just drop it and drop what you're doing

404
00:17:47,222 --> 00:17:48,783
and you say, yes, we can do that.

405
00:17:49,123 --> 00:17:51,045
And that's what expansions are really good for that.

406
00:17:52,225 --> 00:17:55,108
But any small chunks of work will work for that.

407
00:17:56,092 --> 00:17:58,354
Also, if funding gets delayed for a project,

408
00:17:58,655 --> 00:18:00,796
then you can move those expansions up in your schedule.

409
00:18:01,797 --> 00:18:06,221
So once you've found a genre, it's helpful to stick to it.

410
00:18:06,301 --> 00:18:07,682
You can line up your next projects.

411
00:18:07,702 --> 00:18:10,545
You can see once we started doing board game stuff

412
00:18:10,705 --> 00:18:12,707
on the right, we started getting more and more projects

413
00:18:12,747 --> 00:18:14,468
just flowing from one to the next.

414
00:18:14,548 --> 00:18:16,310
The pink ones are the projects our studio has done.

415
00:18:17,622 --> 00:18:19,303
Also, if you stick to a genre, you're

416
00:18:19,324 --> 00:18:21,906
going to get a lot more return on investment for your tools.

417
00:18:22,467 --> 00:18:24,029
So doing board game type of tools,

418
00:18:24,089 --> 00:18:25,851
we have a lot of UI tools where we

419
00:18:25,871 --> 00:18:31,016
can do a lot of transparency icons and careful attention

420
00:18:31,056 --> 00:18:33,119
to draw order in 3D space.

421
00:18:33,539 --> 00:18:34,760
You're going to get more value out

422
00:18:34,780 --> 00:18:36,903
of that in your second, your third, and fourth title.

423
00:18:38,355 --> 00:18:44,018
So you also, again, want to think about who has too much money and not enough video games.

424
00:18:44,378 --> 00:18:45,399
Sometimes that's your players.

425
00:18:45,979 --> 00:18:51,542
There's a big mistake I made with Cannon Brawl, which is it didn't have an existing genre when it came out.

426
00:18:51,703 --> 00:18:54,964
There wasn't really a player base for a real-time artillery game.

427
00:18:55,485 --> 00:19:00,868
So we had to do the work of not only building the game, but building a community for this kind of work.

428
00:19:01,528 --> 00:19:02,869
Not the same thing with board games.

429
00:19:03,009 --> 00:19:06,791
So you can just deliver something that the community is looking for, and it's a little easier.

430
00:19:07,835 --> 00:19:10,417
Here's a picture of where our money comes from as a studio.

431
00:19:10,877 --> 00:19:12,538
You can see we've moved from the longer project

432
00:19:12,578 --> 00:19:15,099
to the shorter ones that are about six months.

433
00:19:15,579 --> 00:19:18,000
And we make a lot of our money on direct sales,

434
00:19:18,080 --> 00:19:20,141
but we still supplement that with grants,

435
00:19:20,462 --> 00:19:23,083
work for hire, partnerships, and contests.

436
00:19:24,384 --> 00:19:27,965
And Race for the Galaxy has been probably our top seller.

437
00:19:28,686 --> 00:19:31,027
It's one of the top card games on iOS,

438
00:19:31,067 --> 00:19:32,788
but we've also had plenty of failures.

439
00:19:34,700 --> 00:19:37,643
The point of all this is that you as an indie studio

440
00:19:37,763 --> 00:19:39,465
can do what you want, whether that's

441
00:19:39,605 --> 00:19:41,146
working on a kooky piece of hardware

442
00:19:41,586 --> 00:19:43,328
or working on a kooky game idea.

443
00:19:44,309 --> 00:19:47,411
But if you don't win the lottery with that,

444
00:19:48,332 --> 00:19:49,413
you're not out of the game.

445
00:19:49,573 --> 00:19:51,595
You just have to balance out your workload

446
00:19:51,835 --> 00:19:52,816
with some safer bets.

447
00:19:53,775 --> 00:19:55,736
We have this idea of what it is to be indie,

448
00:19:56,677 --> 00:20:00,419
to sometimes create this beautiful, glorious magnum opus

449
00:20:00,459 --> 00:20:04,221
that takes seven years to produce, and that's very valid.

450
00:20:04,241 --> 00:20:06,422
This is another way to be indie.

451
00:20:06,482 --> 00:20:07,623
It's definitely not that.

452
00:20:07,683 --> 00:20:11,285
This is being nimble, it's reacting to opportunities,

453
00:20:11,665 --> 00:20:14,927
and staying alive to make those projects that you do love,

454
00:20:15,347 --> 00:20:16,928
withstanding successes and failures.

455
00:20:27,644 --> 00:20:30,866
Hello, I'm Tanya X. Short.

456
00:20:30,946 --> 00:20:32,528
I'm the captain of Kit Fox Games.

457
00:20:33,048 --> 00:20:34,890
And I'm here to present, I guess,

458
00:20:34,970 --> 00:20:38,393
maybe a more traditional idea of what it is to be an indie

459
00:20:38,473 --> 00:20:41,075
in that we still haven't managed to pay ourselves $70,000 a year.

460
00:20:42,814 --> 00:20:46,755
That sounds great, but we are scrappily clawing our way up

461
00:20:47,175 --> 00:20:48,575
every year, increasing our salary

462
00:20:48,615 --> 00:20:51,476
through increasingly successful games, hopefully.

463
00:20:52,216 --> 00:20:54,997
You might know us most through Boyfriend Dungeon.

464
00:20:55,397 --> 00:20:57,637
We also last week announced we were

465
00:20:57,657 --> 00:21:00,958
going to pair with Bay 12 Games to publish Dwarf Fortress.

466
00:21:01,818 --> 00:21:04,038
And all of this does come back to a strategy

467
00:21:04,098 --> 00:21:06,199
that we settled on about five, six years ago.

468
00:21:07,219 --> 00:21:09,139
When we started, we weren't sure what we were doing.

469
00:21:09,180 --> 00:21:11,180
We were just sort of working together

470
00:21:11,620 --> 00:21:15,661
on trying to make a studio together that would survive,

471
00:21:15,701 --> 00:21:17,981
that we could become better designers together.

472
00:21:18,001 --> 00:21:21,602
Oh, the formatting's not great, but it's fine.

473
00:21:22,742 --> 00:21:24,683
We want to make some of the best games in the world,

474
00:21:24,743 --> 00:21:27,243
and in order to do that, we have to be happy,

475
00:21:27,263 --> 00:21:30,184
and in order to be happy and make better and better games,

476
00:21:30,204 --> 00:21:30,984
we have to survive.

477
00:21:31,344 --> 00:21:31,744
And so,

478
00:21:32,804 --> 00:21:36,125
When it all comes down to is every time we ship a game,

479
00:21:36,165 --> 00:21:38,465
we're already in the middle of thinking

480
00:21:38,525 --> 00:21:40,386
about what is the next one, and how do we

481
00:21:40,446 --> 00:21:42,606
help the next one be better than the last one?

482
00:21:42,666 --> 00:21:44,947
Not just better in terms of, I don't know,

483
00:21:45,007 --> 00:21:46,967
review scores or sales or whatever,

484
00:21:47,007 --> 00:21:49,408
but better in terms of how we make them

485
00:21:49,468 --> 00:21:51,108
and how we feel proud of them.

486
00:21:51,789 --> 00:21:55,389
So overall, we have made a lot of choices that

487
00:21:56,790 --> 00:22:03,253
many would call maybe fiscally conservative, safer, less risky business practices.

488
00:22:04,593 --> 00:22:09,195
Now Kickstarter doesn't really fit into any of those goals in theory. In theory, you know,

489
00:22:09,235 --> 00:22:13,057
it obstructs your quality of life, it doesn't let you really practice your craft, and you can't

490
00:22:13,097 --> 00:22:19,940
sustain a studio on it, that's for sure. But this actually does fit into our underlying strategy

491
00:22:20,760 --> 00:22:25,703
of being opportunistic and by always trying to control our own destiny.

492
00:22:26,243 --> 00:22:32,224
So what I mean by opportunistic is our very first game

493
00:22:32,244 --> 00:22:33,584
transition is a really good example.

494
00:22:33,684 --> 00:22:34,905
Our first game was Shattered Planet,

495
00:22:34,925 --> 00:22:37,125
and it was a mobile and PC game.

496
00:22:37,445 --> 00:22:40,406
And we were approaching beta, and the deadline

497
00:22:40,446 --> 00:22:41,306
was coming up fast.

498
00:22:41,606 --> 00:22:42,586
